1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,769
The person who says adamantine, when in plain talk he means immovable, or says coquette,

2
00:00:06,800 --> 00:00:12,050
when we would understand him better if he said flirt, may have a big vocabulary.

3
00:00:12,079 --> 00:00:15,089
But does he have a big thinker's vocabulary?

4
00:00:15,199 --> 00:00:16,290
Probably not.

5
00:00:16,560 --> 00:00:27,329
People who use difficult, high-sounding words and phrases that most folks have to strain themselves to understand are inclined to be overbearing and stuffed shirts,

6
00:00:27,440 --> 00:00:30,850
and stuffed shirts are usually small thinkers.

7
00:00:31,440 --> 00:00:37,570
The important measure of a person's vocabulary is not the size or the number of words he uses.

8
00:00:37,919 --> 00:00:43,010
Rather, the thing that counts, the only thing that counts about one's vocabulary,

9
00:00:43,039 --> 00:00:47,889
is the effect his words and phrases have on his own and others' thinking.

10
00:00:48,479 --> 00:00:50,449
Here is something very basic.

11
00:00:50,719 --> 00:00:53,649
We do not think in words and phrases.

12
00:00:53,839 --> 00:00:57,410
We think only in pictures and or images.

13
00:00:58,079 --> 00:01:00,930
Words are the raw materials of thought.

14
00:01:01,120 --> 00:01:09,730
When spoken or read, that amazing instrument, the mind, automatically converts words and phrases into mind pictures.

15
00:01:10,079 --> 00:01:14,930
Each word, each phrase, creates a slightly different mind picture.

16
00:01:15,279 --> 00:01:20,050
If someone tells you, Jim bought a new split level, you see one picture.

17
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:24,930
But if you're told, Jim bought a new ranch house, you see another picture.

18
00:01:25,279 --> 00:01:32,690
The mind pictures we see are modified by the kinds of words we use to name things and describe things.

19
00:01:33,120 --> 00:01:34,449
Look at it this way.

20
00:01:34,560 --> 00:01:41,250
When you speak or write, you are, in a sense, a projector showing movies in the minds of others,

21
00:01:41,360 --> 00:01:45,730
and the pictures you create determine how you and others react.

22
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:51,089
Suppose you tell a group of people, I'm sorry to report we've failed.

23
00:01:51,199 --> 00:01:52,930
What do these people see?

24
00:01:53,199 --> 00:01:58,610
They see defeat and all the disappointment and grief the word failed conveys.

25
00:01:58,880 --> 00:02:03,889
Now suppose you said instead, here's a new approach that I think will work.

26
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:07,170
They would feel encouraged, ready to try again.

27
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:10,529
Suppose you say, we face a problem.

28
00:02:10,800 --> 00:02:16,209
You have created a picture in the minds of others of something difficult, unpleasant to solve.

29
00:02:16,479 --> 00:02:24,370
Instead, say, we face a challenge, and you create a mind picture of fun, sport, something pleasant to do.

30
00:02:24,800 --> 00:02:31,970
Or tell a group, we incurred a big expense, and people see money spent that will never return.

31
00:02:32,240 --> 00:02:34,449
Indeed, this is unpleasant.

32
00:02:34,639 --> 00:02:41,810
Instead, say, we made a big investment, and people see a picture of something that will return profits later on,

33
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:43,570
a very pleasant sight.

34
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:45,250
The point is this.

35
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:54,449
Big thinkers are specialists in creating positive, forward-looking, optimistic pictures in their own minds and in the minds of others.

36
00:02:54,800 --> 00:03:01,810
To think big, we must use words and phrases that produce big, positive mental images.

